{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958062701/0332.xml":{"full_text":"Summit County Labor New*\n1 PmUtakad Iwrjf Friday by\nH THE SUMMIT COUNTY LABOR NEWS\nT A Non-PmrtUon Natmpapar jwUbM in the bott Interests of\nOrganised Labor and the entire Community.\ni\nEditorial, Advertigmg and Printing Office*\n980 SOUTH HIGH STREET Telephone\u2014PO 2-1110\n^AKRON 11, OHIO _\nthe EXCHANGE PRINTING Co.... .Publisher\nMartinBliman...Editor\nAlex Eigenmacht...Contributing Editor\nAttend m Second Oass Matter May 4, 1923, at Poet OCfloe at\nr Akron, Ohio, under act of March 3, 1897.\nYearly Subscription in Advance..$8.00\nNewa of interact from the various local unions under the Jurisdiction of\nthe Congress at Industrial Organizations, Akron Industrial Union Council,\nthe American Federation at Labor and the Akron Federation of Labor is\nsolicited. All news matter Should reach the editorial office of the Summit\nCounty Labor News not later than Tuesday noon.\nThe Summit County Labor News accepts advertisements from firms not\non the unfair list of the Central Bodies. It must be understood, however,\nthat the editorial policy of this publication is affected in no way by such\nadvertisements.\nQuote Of The Week v*\n\u201cWe have had enough of the pious (talk) that says the sput\nniks were a good thing because they will wake us up, or that the\nreception of the Vice Resident in South America was a good thing\nbecause it showed up the weaknesses in the Good Neighbor policy.\nThis is worse than making a virtue of necessity. It is making a\nvirtue of disaster.\u201d (President A. Whitney Griswold of Yale Uni\nversity in talk to Yale graduating class)\n\u25a0.-.o\nWell, It\u2019s Just A Suggestion\nWhile President Eisenhower was1 waiting at the Washington\nNational Airport to welcome Vice President Nixon back from Latin\nAmerica, Congressman Sid Simpson hollered to the President,\n\u201cYou gonna play golf this afternoon?\u201d\n\u201cNo,\u201d the President shouted back. \"I\u2019m going to work.\u201d\nThen, noting that the reporters were not making notes of this\nannounced intention to work, the President commented, \u201cIt al\nways gets into the papers when I play golf. Why isn\u2019t it mentioned\nwhen I stay in the office and work?\u201d\nWhen a Democrat read this in a column by George Dixon, he\nsuggested that perhaps the President had a good point and that\nthe papers should drop those little stories which read, \u201cPresident\nEisenhower took advantage of sunny weather today to go to the\nBurning Tree Club in nearby Maryland for a round of golf.\u201d\nInstead, he added, the papers should give us the real news,\nsuch as, \u201cPresident Eisenhower took advantage of a cloudburst\nand hailstorm to spend an afternoon at work in the White House.\u201d\n-o\u2014\nThe California Primary\nSenator William F. Knowland, running on a platform that\nfeatured a so-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d law, took quite a drubbing in\nthe California primary from State Attorney Edmund G. Brown\nwho opposed such a law.\nIt is possible in California, where candidates can run on both\nthe Democratic and Republican ticket, to judge the popularity of\nthe candidates among voters of both parties.\nBoth Knowland and Brown were nominated by their parties\nfor the Governor\u2019s office but in the total two-party, vote, Know\nland was snowed under by 60,000 votes.\nThere has been much speculation whether Knpwland\u2019s stand\nfor a \u201cright-to-work\u201d law was the primary reason for his thump\ning and on the role Labor played in Brown\u2019s impressive showing.\nThe New York Times labor reported, Joseph A. Loftus, made this\ncomment in a column on the California primary:\n\u201cVoting in the industrial areas of the state indicated that\nlabor was influential in piling up a big margin for Knowland\u2019s op\nponent in the total Republican-Democratic returns.\u201d\nLawrence E. Davies, writing in The Times from San Fran\ncisco, said that Knowland\u2019s \u201cright-to-work\u201d stand \u201cbrought out a\nwidespread union-sponsored registration campaign in the spring,\nwith another to follow this fall. Labor\u2019s efforts in registration\nare credited largely with adding \u201ctwo and one half* Democrats to\nthe rolls for every additional Republican.\u201d\nClinton L. Mosher, political reporter for the San Francisco\nExaminer, noted that Knowland \u201cchose advocacy of the highly\ncontroversial right-to-work proposal, thus getting the laboring\nman into action against him.\u201d\nThis is not an effort to claim a Labor \u201cvictory\u201d in the Cali\nfornia primary. There are always many reasons why a particular\ncandidate runs well or badly. And it is unwise to speculate too\nmuch from this distance.\nHowever, from the comments so far, it is safe to Mumhido\nthat the worker is aware of the \u201cright-to-work\u201d threat and that\nthe \u201cright-to-work\u201d issue brings the worker to the polls in greater\nnumbers.\no' ...V..,\nHave Money, Will YOU Travel?\n_ \u201cThe right-to-work\u201d boys are loosening the strings around\ntheir money bags to make certain they get enough signatures to\nput their compulsory open shop amendment on the November\nballot.\nAnd the manner in which they are soliciting signature soli\ncitors is typical of their whole \u201cright-to-work\u201d operation: They\ntell only a small part of the story.\nFor example, they have just run a number of ads for petition\ny, circulators in a number of college newspapers throughout the\nstate in which they hold out promises'of great financial rewards\nwithout stating the name of the hiring organization (Ohioans\nFor Right To Work) or the kind of work involved.\nFollowing is the ad that appeared in the May 28 issue of The\nLantern, the daily student newspaper published at Ohio State\nUniversity:\n\u201cSummer Jobs (6 weeks NOT selling). Hiring 50 neat, per\nsonable COLLEGE! ben. Will travel In small groups with super\nvisor. Present employes averaging $100 per week. Apply Now\n.beds work June 15. Get applications in Person at 50 N. 3rd\nStreet/*\nIt happens that 50 N. Third St, Columbus, is the headquar\nters for \u201cOhioans For Right To Work,\u201d although an unsuspecting\ncollege student would have no way of knowing this from the ad.\nThe same type of ad has been run in at least three other school\npaMn. That means Ohioans For Right To Work is willing to pay\n200 students a total, of 3120,000 in a six-week period to circulate\npetitions!\nCopies of agreements between \u201cright-to-work\u201d forces and\nhind drculators which state that \u201ccompensation for circulators\nvffl be an #18 pei? day drawing account.\u201d\nThis nput be rather disillusioning to some people who might\nStudy Politics and Joblessness\nAt Labor Summer Schools\nMora labor education summer\nschools are beta# held this year and\nmore locals are sending students\nthan ever before, a survey by file\nAFLrdO Dept, of Education indi\ncates, but the recession and its effect\non employment are having an impact.\nSeveral of the echools, which h\nother years have operated for a full\nweek, have been cut back to three\ndays, the compilation shows.\nHie economic downturn is having\nits effect on the programs, too. Last\nyear the emphasis was on ethical\npractices, psychology and widespread\ninterest in the Steelworkers \"liberal\narts\u201d program at Pennsylvania State\nUniversity, it is recalled in the de\npartment's publication, Education\nNews and Views.\n\"Number One problem which win\nbe kicked around at all summer\nschools,\u201d the article adds, *Vill be\nan analysis of the recession and the\nfailure of the labor movemeat to\nmobilise enough strength to paae Hs\nbasic anti-recession legislative pro\ngram In Congress.\n\"Inevitably, discussions of the re\ncession will move into the Novem\nber elections. Union schools will ex\nploit the economic issues and the fail\nure of Congress to move local un\nions to get more people registered\nand to get more votes for congress- I\nmen who will support anti-recession\nlegislation. In states where \u2018rigtot-to\nwork\u2019 is on the ballot, this will be\nuppermost in the programs.\u201d\nAs in other years, there also will\nbe stress on local problems in work\nshop sessions on local union admin\nistration, stewards\u2019 training, public\nspeaking, parliamentary procedure\nand how to rum better meetings.\nTwelve of the schools are being\nsponsored or co-sponsored by the cen\ntral bodies in 20 states. Two courses\nInvolve AFL-CIO deportments a\ntime study and wage incentive insti\ntute at the University of Wisconsin,\nMadison, Wis., from duly 20 to 26,\nand a Community Services Activi\nGas Appliance\n\u201cWall\u201d to Be\nOn Market\nA new concept in kitchen appli\nance design soon will be on the mar\nket in the form of the gas \u201cMulti-,\nmatic Wall,\u201d a single unit combining\ncooking, laundering, refrigeration,\nwater heating and househeating facil\nities.\nThe unit, designed by Walter Dor\nwin Teague Associates, was assem\nbled and tested by engineers at the\nAmerican Gas Association Laboratory\nIn Cleveland. Hie space-saving \u201cappli\nance wall\u201d Is the result of more than\ntwo years of extensive research.\nA single, self-contained appliance,\nit will be delivered complete with all\nnecessary plumbing, electrical and\nflue systems read for operation.. Its\nsize was established to best fit into\nmost house plans and to accommodate\nthe most desirable service features.\nIt is 10 feet long, 7\u2018-ll\u201d high and\n2\u2019-8\\\" deep.\nContained in the unit are an oven\nbroiler, a wash-dryer, a water heater,\na refrigerator and furnace. All use a\nsingle fuel\u2014gas.\nAccording to AX5.A engineers, the\nmajor advantages of the unit range\nfrom convenience to economy.\nThey point out that the \"Multim&Uc\nWall\u201d is a money-saver because its\npurchase price will be less than the\ncombined cost of the included appli\nances if they were bought individu\nally. Extra Installation costs for sepa\nrate appliances are eliminated, and\nsince the self-contained venting sys\ntem makes a chimney unnecessary,\ncost of chimney can be excluded. In\naddition, the use of gas in five ways\nwill enable owners to take full ad\nvantage of the tower cost of gaa as\na fuel.\nThe compactness ef the wait per\nmits most household tasks to be per\nformed within an area of a few feet.\nFeed storage and cooking are pro\nvided for in ike unit. Unique\ndange-top bnrners fold late toe wall\nto provide extra counter space.\ninclusion of laundering and house\nheating facilities in the \u201cwall\";, elimi\nnates the need for. a basement or\nutility room.\nDespite its compactness, the unit\ndoes not skimp on modern features.\nThe RCA Whirlpool refrigerator in\ncludes automatic defrosting end the\nautomatic ieamaksr; two of the five\nburners utilise thermostatically con\ntrolled burners. Jn addition to the\nappliances the win inchidee. there Is\nId cubic feet of storage space in cabi\nnets.\nties institute A*g. to at Pena\nState IJnlvcnltf, University Park,\nPa. The oUwn are sponsored by In\ndividual anions or groups of anions.\nOhio Sales Tax\nRevenue Off\nCollection* from the selective sales\ntax for the weak ending June 7,\namounted to $3,580,609, Treasurer of\nState Roger W. Tracy reported this\nweek.\nThis represents a drop of $747,603,\nor 17.51 per cent from, the $4,268,212\nwhich the tax produced for the cor\nresponding week of last year.\nWith the single exception of Ma\nhoning County, the eight major urban\ncounties accounted for $568,986, or\n60.2 per cent, of the -total sag for the\nweek\u2019s comparison.\nCumulative collections for the fis\ncal year, to date, amounted to $206,\n701,918, Tracy said, pointing out that\nthe cumulative loea for the year is\n$10,062,284, or 4.63 per cent, from\nthe corresponding period of last year.\nThe weekly report showed 27 coun\nties with- collections in excess of a\nyear ago, while the five select coun\nties\u2014Fairfield, Gallia, Meigs, Mon\nroe and Washington\u2014continue to hold\non to their respective slight excesses\nin cumulative collections this year\nover last year.\nUnions Serve\nAs Cushion\nTo Slump\nAmerica can thank its unions tar\npreventing a deeper recession than\nthat It is now experiencing. This is a\nrecession with one. major difference;\nthere has been no mass pay-cutting.\nPrior to the rise of industrial un\nions, past slumps have been marked\nby large scale wage cutting which has\nfed upon Itself and caused the slumps\nto turn into panics.\nThat was the base in 1929 when\nmany firms retrenched by cutting\nwage levels. The result was a continu\nal shrinkage of consumer purchasing\npower that ultimately led to the\nparalysis of 1932^, M\nConservative e&otmnlets and busi\nnessmen have given evidence of what\nthey would like to impose upon the\ncountry. They speak incessantly\naboult \"rigidities in the wage struc\nture\" as the cause of the recession\nand as the reason for its prolongation.\nWlhat they mean, quite obviously, is\nthat they would like to eee business\nmaintain high profits by cutting\ni wages.\n,It Is a tribute to America\u2019s organ\nised workers that t|ie employers have\nnot attempted any .onslaught upon the\nwage stincture. The fact is diet de\nspite the recession, unionised work\ners are winning wage Incresses, al\nthough not in the same amounts as a\nyear ago.\nWhat employers would do If tin\nions were not around was well illus\ntrated by recent events at Phi loo\nRadio. This company cut its white\ncollar workers wages by five per\ncent. Organised production workers,\non the other hand, wen 'a wage in\ncrease of five cents par hour.\nThere la evidence that the white\ncoder group which escaped the initial\nimpact of the recession now is being\nhit. The publication. Business Week,\nhas pointed out that layoffs and short\nworkweeks are becoming more pro\nnounced in white .collar areas, .and\nthat white collar workers are feeling\nwage cuts as well.\nBaalsesa Week reported that up to\n\u25a0ow \"cutting salaries was ofted con\nsidered impossible at a thus when\nwages of unionised employed stayed\nOBuetaTt or, under eouss^ contracts,\nwere about to go up,\n\"Thu can still hear these arguments\nwidely\u2014but among some hard hit\ncompanies, they\u2019re becoming leas im\nportant than the need to cut costs in\noffice areas. In the last month or\neo, cute have been doming faster.\"\nt>V\n-\u2014in..; i iHMW.-ii' I i\nhave been led to believe that this \"demand*\u2019 for eo-calj^d \u201cright-to\nwork\" law was a spontaneous demand that sprang fiom the grass\nroots.\nNow it appears that it isn't springing from anything but in\nstead must be sprang by something the same color a|\u00bb grass!\nFees Permitted in\n\"Work\" States,\nJudge Rules\nNon-union workers nun in bright\nto wwk\" stat\u00ab\u00bb\u2014can be ordered to\npay a union an amount equivalent to\ndues if they come under a collective\nbargaining agreement, according to\nan Indiana Judge.\nfudge Joseph V. Stodola filled that\neven though state leer may outlaw\nunion shop agreements, this does not\nmean that labor and management\ncannot reach agreement that every\nworker most either Join the union\nor pay it the same amount paid by\nunion members.\nSuperior Court Judge Stodola de\nclared that \u201cthis payment of the fair\nShare of representation is completely\ndistinct and substantially different\nfrom compulsory membership in a un\nion.\u201d\nIn making his decision, the judge\ndenied a petition by the Meade Elec\ntric Oo. of Hammond,'Ind., tor an in\njunction against the International\nBrotherhood of Electrical Workers.\nThe company sought to prevent the\nIBEW from including In a proposed\ncontract a clause permitting non\nmembers to \u201cpay the union an amount\nof money equal to that paid by other\nemployes in the bargaining unit who\nare members of the union.\u201d\nAccording to the Judge, the pro\nposed clause does not violate the 1957\nIndiana \u201cright-to-work\u201d law that pro\nhibits making onion membership a\ncondition Of employment.\nShould Judge Stodol&'s ruling be\napplied on a nationwide basis, the\nentire \u201cright to work\u201d hoax could\nquickly disappear.\nRAC. BROADCAST TO\nHONOR DUlintSKT\nA special radio program honoring\nDavid Dublnsky'e 25 year* as presi\ndent of the Inti. Ladles Garment\nWorkers Union will be broadcast over\nthe National Broadcast Co. network\nSunday.\nAFL-CIO President George Meany\nwill participate.\nthe program is being sponsored\nby the Jewish Theological Seminary\non its series entitled The Eternal\nLight. The script was prepared by\nHamy Gerah.\nYour\nElection\nLaws\n-U:'\n.By TED W. BMWV\nof State of\nWhile the law provides for recounts,\nand properly so, the 1958 Primaries\nagain proved the contention that very\nstay recounts result in a change of\nwlnw.\nThe tact is that the unofficial tele\nphone results, which were sent to the\nSecretary of. State\u2019s office on state\nraces and on Representative to Con\ngress election night, were not too far\ndifferent from the figures established\nby the unofficial report, mailed the\nnext.day or the figures established\nin the official canvass.\nNecessarily, the talbulatibn of votes\ncost must be hastily done by the 88\nCounty Boards of Elections on elec\ntion night, hut with some exceptions,\nof course, the figures are usually near\nthe official. Sometimes, either in tabu\nlation-or in the transmission of a re\nport over the telephone, figures are\ntransposed or some other, error is\nmade; but with the modern-day\nmethods with which -the Boards of\nElections have surrounded themselves,\n'and with the careful checking system\nused in the Secretary of State\u2019s of\nfice, these error are usually soon\ncaught.\nVoting machines have not only\nspeeded up returns in the precincts\nwhere they are used, but they have\nJLQVIRTniNS AND PUBLICATION\nHE